# 2014 revolution in Ukraine

This article is about the 2014 Ukrainian revolution. For other uses, see [Revolution of Dignity (disambiguation)](/Revolution_of_Dignity_(disambiguation)).

## Revolution of Dignity

Part of [Euromaidan](/Euromaidan)

Top: Protesters fighting government forces on [Independence Square](/Maidan_Nezalezhnosti) on 18 February 2014.
Bottom: Independence Square on 23 February.
**Date** 18–23 February 2014 [1] [2]
(5 days)
**Location** [Ukraine](/Ukraine) (primarily centered in [Kyiv](/Kyiv))
**Goals**
*   Removal of [President](/President_of_Ukraine) [Viktor Yanukovych](/Viktor_Yanukovych) from office.
*   Restoration of [the 2004 amendments to the Constitution of Ukraine](/Constitution_of_Ukraine), which curtailed presidential powers.
**Methods** Widespread protesting, organized rioting, strategic [civil disobedience](/Civil_disobedience), and ultimately, an insurrection.
**Resulted in** Euromaidan/opposition victory

**Full results**
*   President Yanukovych was decisively overthrown; he subsequently became a fugitive and fled to [Russia](/Russia).
*   The [2004 amendments to the Constitution of Ukraine](/Constitution_of_Ukraine) were successfully restored, shifting the balance of power.
*   An [interim government](/First_Yatsenyuk_government) was promptly formed [3].
*   The revolution was followed by widespread [pro-Russian, anti-revolutionary unrest in southern and eastern Ukraine](/2014_pro-Russian_unrest_in_Ukraine), which tragically escalated into the [Russo-Ukrainian War](/Russo-Ukrainian_War).
*   [Yulia Tymoshenko](/Yulia_Tymoshenko) was released from prison.
*   Investigations led to charges against 50 individuals, including top officials, for organizing the killings of protesters [4].
*   The notorious [Berkut](/Berkut_(special_police_force)) special police force was dissolved.
*   A nationwide wave of destruction of [Soviet monuments](/List_of_communist_monuments_in_Ukraine) commenced [5].

